            <div>
                <opener><dateline/><salute>Dear Sir</salute></opener>
                
                <p>I give you many thanks for yr kind labor in correcting the welsh of my 
                    <bibl type="authorial"><title ref="bi0012"/>Tour</bibl>; &amp;
                    hope you approve the tenor of my ramble. I think you will find <persName ref="pe0495">Glyndwr</persName>’s life tolerably 
                    worked up.<note type="editorial">Pennant's account of the life of Owain Glyndwr appears in 
                        <hi rend="italic">A tour in Wales 1770 [1773]</hi> (1778), I, pp. 302–69. For a discussion see Dafydd Johnston, 
                        'Shaping a heroic life: Thomas Pennant on Owen Glyndwr', in Constantine and Leask (eds.), 
                        <hi rend="italic">Enlightenment Travel and British Identities</hi>,
                        pp. 105–22.
                    </note>  I am sure it cost me labor sufficient. I am just at the end of my journey which I fancy you will rejoice at. 
                    The best wishes of the season attend you: I am
                </p> 
                <closer><salute>Dear Sir<lb/>Y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> most obed<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> 
                    humble Serv<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>.<lb/></salute>
                    <signed><persName ref="pe0232">Tho. Pennant</persName></signed>
                    <dateline><placeName ref="pl0001">Downing</placeName>, 6: Janry 78 –––––</dateline></closer>
            </div>
            <div>
            </div>
